variants.name: RecurrentBroadcast

variants.name: RecurrentPrank
variants.description: A recurrent prank triggered by a `vm.startPrank()` call is currently active.

variants.name: Resume

structs.name: FsMetadata
structs.description:
Metadata information about a file.
 This structure is returned from the `fsMetadata` function and represents known
 metadata about a file such as its permissions, size, modification
 times, etc.

fields.name: isDir
fields.description: True if this metadata is for a directory.

fields.name: isSymlink
fields.description: True if this metadata is for a symlink.

fields.name: length
fields.description: The size of the file, in bytes, this metadata is for.

fields.name: readOnly
fields.description: True if this metadata is for a readonly (unwritable) file.

fields.name: modified
fields.description: The last modification time listed in this metadata.

fields.name: accessed
fields.description: The last access time of this metadata.

fields.name: created
fields.description: The creation time listed in this metadata.

structs.name: Wallet
structs.description: A wallet with a public and private key.

fields.name: addr
fields.description: The wallet's address.

fields.name: publicKeyX
fields.description: The wallet's public key `X`.

fields.name: publicKeyY
fields.description: The wallet's public key `Y`.

fields.name: privateKey
fields.description: The wallet's private key.

fields.name: exitCode
fields.description: The exit code of the call.

fields.name: stdout
fields.description: The optionally hex-decoded `stdout` data.

fields.name: stderr
fields.description: The `stderr` data.

structs.name: ChainInfo
structs.description: Information on the chain and fork.

fields.name: forkId
fields.description: The fork identifier. Set to zero if no fork is active.

fields.name: chainId
fields.description: The chain ID of the current fork.

fields.name: chainInfo
fields.description: The chain and fork the access occurred.

fields.name: kind
fields.description:
The kind of account access that determines what the account is.
 If kind is Call, DelegateCall, StaticCall or CallCode, then the account is the callee.
 If kind is Create, then the account is the newly created account.
 If kind is SelfDestruct, then the account is the selfdestruct recipient.
 If kind is a Resume, then account represents a account context that has resumed.

fields.name: account
fields.description:
The account that was accessed.
 It's either the account created, callee or a selfdestruct recipient for CREATE, CALL or SELFDESTRUCT.

fields.name: accessor
fields.description: What accessed the account.

fields.name: initialized
fields.description:
If the account was initialized or empty prior to the access.
 An account is considered initialized if it has code, a
 non-zero nonce, or a non-zero balance.

fields.name: oldBalance
fields.description: The previous balance of the accessed account.

fields.name: newBalance
fields.description:
The potential new balance of the accessed account.
 That is, all balance changes are recorded here, even if reverts occurred.

fields.name: deployedCode
fields.description: Code of the account deployed by CREATE.

fields.name: value
fields.description: Value passed along with the account access

fields.name: data
fields.description: Input data provided to the CREATE or CALL

fields.name: reverted
fields.description: If this access reverted in either the current or parent context.

fields.name: storageAccesses
fields.description: An ordered list of storage accesses made during an account access operation.

fields.name: depth
fields.description: Call depth traversed during the execution of the function

fields.name: account
fields.description: The account whose storage was accessed.

fields.name: slot
fields.description: The slot that was accessed.

fields.name: isWrite
fields.description: If the access was a write.

fields.name: previousValue
fields.description: The previous value of the slot.

fields.name: newValue
fields.description: The new value of the slot.

fields.name: reverted
fields.description: If the access was reverted.

func.description:
Copies the contents of one file to another. This function will **overwrite** the contents of `to`.
On success, the total number of bytes copied is returned and it is equal to the length of the `to` file as reported by `metadata`.
Both `from` and `to` are relative to the project root.
func.declaration: function copyFile(string calldata from, string calldata to) external returns (uint64 copied);

func.description:
Creates a new, empty directory at the provided path.
This cheatcode will revert in the following situations, but is not limited to just these cases:
- User lacks permissions to modify `path`.
- A parent of the given path doesn't exist and `recursive` is false.
- `path` already exists and `recursive` is false.
`path` is relative to the project root.
func.declaration: function createDir(string calldata path, bool recursive) external;

func.description:
Prepare an expected log with (bool checkTopic1, bool checkTopic2, bool checkTopic3, bool checkData.).
Call this function, then emit an event, then call a function. Internally after the call, we check if
logs were emitted in the expected order with the expected topics and data (as specified by the booleans).
func.declaration: function expectEmit(bool checkTopic1, bool checkTopic2, bool checkTopic3, bool checkData) external;

func.description: Same as the previous method, but also checks supplied address against emitting contract.
func.declaration: function expectEmit(bool checkTopic1, bool checkTopic2, bool checkTopic3, bool checkData, address emitter) external;

func.description:
Prepare an expected log with all topic and data checks enabled.
Call this function, then emit an event, then call a function. Internally after the call, we check if
logs were emitted in the expected order with the expected topics and data.
func.declaration: function expectEmit() external;

func.description: Same as the previous method, but also checks supplied address against emitting contract.
func.declaration: function expectEmit(address emitter) external;

to the set.

func.description:
Reads the directory at the given path recursively, up to `maxDepth`.
`maxDepth` defaults to 1, meaning only the direct children of the given directory will be returned.
Follows symbolic links if `followLinks` is true.

Reads a symbolic link, returning the path that the link points to.
This cheatcode will revert in the following situations, but is not limited to just these cases:
- `path` is not a symbolic link.

func.description:
Removes a directory at the provided path.
This cheatcode will revert in the following situations, but is not limited to just these cases:
- `path` doesn't exist.
- `path` isn't a directory.
- User lacks permissions to modify `path`.
- The directory is not empty and `recursive` is false.
`path` is relative to the project root.
func.declaration: function removeDir(string calldata path, bool recursive) external;

func.description:
Removes a file from the filesystem.
This cheatcode will revert in the following situations, but is not limited to just these cases:
- `path` points to a directory.
- The file doesn't exist.
- The user lacks permissions to remove the file.
`path` is relative to the project root.
func.declaration: function removeFile(string calldata path) external;

func.description:
Revert the state of the EVM to a previous snapshot
Takes the snapshot ID to revert to.
Returns `true` if the snapshot was successfully reverted.
Returns `false` if the snapshot does not exist.
**Note:** This does not automatically delete the snapshot. To delete the snapshot use `deleteSnapshot`.
func.declaration: function revertTo(uint256 snapshotId) external returns (bool success);

func.description:
Revert the state of the EVM to a previous snapshot and automatically deletes the snapshots
Takes the snapshot ID to revert to.
Returns `true` if the snapshot was successfully reverted and deleted.
Returns `false` if the snapshot does not exist.
func.declaration: function revertToAndDelete(uint256 snapshotId) external returns (bool success);

(at this call depth only) create transactions that can later be signed and sent onchain.
